Compute Statistics

Code 
# compute wap and bidaskspread 
stock1 <- stock1 %>%
  mutate(
    WAP = (bid_price1 * ask_size1 + ask_price1 * bid_size1) / (bid_size1 + ask_size1),
    BidAskSpread = ask_price1 / bid_price1 - 1
  )

# compute log returns per timeid (with 0s for unchanged waps) 
log_r1 <- list()
time_IDs <- unique(stock1$time_id)[1:500]  # first 500 time_ids

for (i in seq_along(time_IDs)) {
  sec <- stock1 %>% filter(time_id == time_IDs[i]) %>% pull(seconds_in_bucket)
  price <- stock1 %>% filter(time_id == time_IDs[i]) %>% pull(WAP)

  log_r <- log(price[-1] / price[-length(price)])
  log_r1[[i]] <- data.frame(time = sec[-1], log_return = log_r)

  # identify timestamps with no change or missing values
  time.no.change <- setdiff(1:600, log_r1[[i]]$time)
  if (length(time.no.change) > 0) {
    zero_df <- data.frame(time = time.no.change, log_return = 0)
    log_r1[[i]] <- rbind(log_r1[[i]], zero_df)
    log_r1[[i]] <- log_r1[[i]][order(log_r1[[i]]$time), ]
  }
}

# compute realized volatility
bucket_size <- 20
comp_vol <- function(x) sqrt(sum(x^2))
vol <- list()

for (i in seq_along(log_r1)) {
  log_r1[[i]] <- log_r1[[i]] %>%
    mutate(time_bucket = ceiling(time / bucket_size))
  
  vol[[i]] <- aggregate(log_return ~ time_bucket, log_r1[[i]], FUN = comp_vol)
  colnames(vol[[i]]) <- c("time_bucket", "volatility")
}

1. Log Returns Plot

  • This plot shows the log returnsÂ per secondÂ over the full 600-second (10-minute) window for one trading session (time_id 200).

    • High-frequency dips and spikes: These show price volatility over short time periods.

    • Low fluctuation periods: When log returns are near zero, it indicates that the weighted average price, or WAP, hasnât changed significantly.

    • Log return = 0 spikes: These result from your decision to incorporate 0-return points in cases when WAP remained unchanged, which is a wise move to maintain temporal continuity.

The price movementâs microstructure. Particularly when calculating realized volatility, relatively tiny variations can have an impact.

2. Realized Volatility Plot

  • This plotÂ shows the actual volatility for the same session broken down into 20-second buckets.

  • A popular stand-in for market activity, volatility is computed as the square root of the sum of squared log returns inside each bucket.

    • While later eras (buckets 20â30) exhibit significantly increased volatility, other periods (such as buckets 1â10) exhibit moderate to low volatility.

    • There is a clear growing trend, which might mean that later in the periodÂ there will be more trading activity or price instability.

This illustrates the volatilityâs time trend. Aids in modeling (for example, forecasting future bucket volatility based on historical data), recognizing spikes in market activity, and influencing the temporal weighting of your model (more recent buckets can be more important).

Estimation and prediction

Code 
# ACF plot for log returns and realised volatility of time_id = 200
acf(log_r1[[200]]$log_return, main = "ACF plot for log returns")
Code 
acf(vol[[200]]$volatility, main = "ACF plot for realised volatility")

ACF Plot for Log Returns

  • Little to noÂ autocorrelation is seen at any latency in the log returnsâ autocorrelation function (ACF).

  • All bars (except lag 0) Â fall under the blue significance boundaries, indicating that the values are statistically identical to zero.

  • Given that financial returns are typically highly uncorrelated, this is predicted behavior for log returns.

  • It implies that it is difficult to make direct predictions from historical values since the log return time series is near white noise.

ACF Plot for Realized Volatility

  • Particularly at shorter delays, the realized volatility (calculated in 20s bins) shows substantial autocorrelation.

  • Particularly from lag 1 to 5, a number of bars are much above the significance thresholds.

  • This demonstrates volatility clustering: periods of low volatility are likely to be followed by low volatility, and times of high volatility by high volatility.

  • This supports the use of historical volatility as a predictor in GARCH or HAV-RV models.

list.reg <- list() 
stock1 <- stock1 %>% mutate(time_bucket = ceiling(seconds_in_bucket / 20),
                            num_order = bid_size1 + ask_size1 + bid_size2 + ask_size2)
len.train <- length(vol.train[[1]]$volatility)

for (i in 1 : length(vol)) {
  stats.bucket <- stock1 %>% 
    filter(time_id == time_IDs[i] & time_bucket != 0) %>% 
    select(c(BidAskSpread, WAP, num_order, time_bucket)) 
  # for each 20-sec time bucket, compute the following statistics
  mean.price <- aggregate(WAP ~ time_bucket, data = stats.bucket, FUN = mean)
  mean.order <- aggregate(num_order ~ time_bucket, data = stats.bucket, FUN = mean)
  mean.BAS <- aggregate(BidAskSpread ~ time_bucket, data = stats.bucket, FUN = mean)
  list.reg[[i]] <- data.frame(volatility = vol.train[[i]]$volatility[-1], 
                              price = mean.price$WAP[1:(len.train - 1)],
                              order = mean.order$num_order[1:(len.train - 1)],
                              BidAskSpread = mean.BAS$BidAskSpread[1:(len.train - 1)])
}

global_reg_data <- data.frame()

for (i in 1:length(vol.train)) {
  len.train <- nrow(vol.train[[i]])

  stats.bucket <- stock1 %>% 
    filter(time_id == time_IDs[i], time_bucket != 0) %>%
    select(time_id, BidAskSpread, WAP, num_order, time_bucket)

  mean.price <- aggregate(WAP ~ time_bucket, data = stats.bucket, mean)
  mean.order <- aggregate(num_order ~ time_bucket, data = stats.bucket, mean)

    BidAskSpread = mean.BAS$BidAskSpread[1:(len.train - 1)]
  )

  global_reg_data <- rbind(global_reg_data, temp_df)
}

HAV-RV Model

The HAV-RV model directly predicts the time series of realized volatility.

Code 
list.HAV <- list()

for (i in 1 : length(vol)) {
  mean.vol <- rep(0, len.train - 5)
  for (j in 1 : 5) {
    mean.vol <- mean.vol + vol.train[[i]]$volatility[j : (j + len.train - 6)] / 5
  }
  list.HAV[[i]] <- data.frame(vol = vol.train[[i]]$volatility[-(1:5)], 
                              vol_1 = vol.train[[i]]$volatility[5:(len.train - 1)],
                              mean_vol_5 = mean.vol)
}

# quarticity
comp_quar <- function(x) length(x) / 3 * sum(x^4)
quar <- lapply(log_r1, function(df) {
  q <- aggregate(log_return ~ time_bucket, df, comp_quar)
  colnames(q) <- c("time_bucket", "quarticity")
  q
})

HAV.ols.models <- list()
HAV.wls.models <- list()

for (i in seq_along(vol)) {
  HAV.ols.models[[i]] <- lm(vol ~ vol_1 + mean_vol_5, list.HAV[[i]])
  HAV.wls.models[[i]] <- lm(vol ~ vol_1 + mean_vol_5, list.HAV[[i]],
                            weights = list.HAV[[i]]$vol_1 /
                              sqrt(quar[[i]]$quarticity[5:(len.train - 1)]))
}

XGBoostÂ 

Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost), is a robust tree-based ensemble model that automatically selects features, manages outliers and skewed data well, and captures non-linear correlations. It works well with big structured datasets and is fast and scalable. XGBoost does not depend on rigid assumptions like normality or stationarity, in contrast to models like ARMA-GARCH or linear regression.

Code 
# compute log returns before using it
stock1 <- stock1 %>%
  group_by(time_id) %>%
  arrange(seconds_in_bucket, .by_group = TRUE) %>%
  mutate(log_return = log(WAP / lag(WAP))) %>%
  ungroup()

features <- stock1 %>%
  group_by(time_id) %>%
  summarise(
    WAP_mean = mean(WAP),
    WAP_sd = sd(WAP),
    BidAskSpread_mean = mean(BidAskSpread),
    BidAskSpread_sd = sd(BidAskSpread),
    log_return_sd = sd(log_return, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# computes realized volatility per time_id using squared log returns â a standard proxy for volatility
target <- stock1 %>%
  group_by(time_id) %>%
  summarise(realized_volatility = sqrt(sum(log_return^2, na.rm = TRUE)))

# combines features and target into a single dataset for supervised learning
final_df <- left_join(features, target, by = "time_id")

# 80/20 training vs testing
split_idx <- createDataPartition(final_df$realized_volatility, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train <- final_df[split_idx, ]
test <- final_df[-split_idx, ]

# removes the id and target variable from input features, resulting a clean numeric matrix  
X_train <- as.matrix(select(train, -time_id, -realized_volatility))
y_train <- train$realized_volatility
X_test <- as.matrix(select(test, -time_id, -realized_volatility))
y_test <- test$realized_volatility

# trains a regression model (predicting volatility, a continuous value) using 100 boosting rounds
xgb_model <- xgboost(
  data = X_train,
  label = y_train,
  nrounds = 100,
  objective = "reg:squarederror",
  verbose = 0
)
Code 
# ranks how important each feature is in splitting the trees â helpful for explaining what drives volatility in the model

Assessing the model (Prediction)

Linear & HAV-RV Validation Predictions

Code 
pred.lm <- list()
pred.hav <- list()
list.reg.val <- list()

for (i in seq_along(vol)) {
  len.val <- length(vol.val[[i]]$volatility)

  stats.bucket <- stock1 %>% 
    filter(time_id == time_IDs[i] & time_bucket != 0) %>%
    select(BidAskSpread, WAP, num_order, time_bucket)

  mean.price <- aggregate(WAP ~ time_bucket, stats.bucket, mean)
  mean.order <- aggregate(num_order ~ time_bucket, stats.bucket, mean)
  mean.BAS <- aggregate(BidAskSpread ~ time_bucket, stats.bucket, mean)

  # feature matrix
  list.reg.val[[i]] <- data.frame(
    volatility = vol.val[[i]]$volatility,
    price = mean.price$WAP[len.train:(len.train + len.val - 1)],
    order = mean.order$num_order[len.train:(len.train + len.val - 1)],
    BidAskSpread = mean.BAS$BidAskSpread[len.train:(len.train + len.val - 1)]
  )

  # predictions
  pred.lm[[i]] <- predict(lm.models[[i]], newdata = list.reg.val[[i]])
  pred.hav[[i]] <- predict(HAV.wls.models[[i]], newdata = list.HAV[[i]])
}

Evaluate All Models

Code 
library(Metrics)

qlike <- function(actual, predicted) {
  mean((actual / predicted) - log(actual / predicted) - 1, na.rm = TRUE)
}

evaluate_model <- function(true, pred) {
  data.frame(
    MAE = mae(true, pred),
    RMSE = rmse(true, pred),
    R2 = R2(pred, true),
    QLIKE = qlike(true, pred)
  )
}
Code 
y_true <- sapply(vol.val[1:100], function(df) df$volatility[1])
Code 
# first prediction from each model's validation predictions
y_reg   <- sapply(pred.lm[1:100], function(x) x[1])
y_hav   <- sapply(pred.hav[1:100], function(x) x[1])
y_xgb   <- pred_xgb[1:100]
Code 
evaluate_model_xgb <- function(true, pred) {
  true <- as.numeric(true)
  pred <- as.numeric(pred)
  data.frame(
    MAE = mae(true, pred),
    RMSE = rmse(true, pred),
    R2 = caret::R2(pred, true), 
    QLIKE = qlike(true, pred)
  )
}


results_comp <- rbind(
  Linear  = evaluate_model(y_true, y_reg),
  HAV_RV  = evaluate_model(y_true, y_hav),
  XGBoost = evaluate_model_xgb(y_test, pred_xgb)  
)
